24.3.0

Highlights

This release is a milestone: it fixes Black's first CVE security vulnerability. If you run Black on untrusted input, or if you habitually put thousands of leading tab characters in your docstrings, you are strongly encouraged to upgrade immediately to fix CVE-2024-21503.

This release also fixes a bug in Black's AST safety check that allowed Black to make incorrect changes to certain f-strings that are valid in Python 3.12 and higher.

Stable style

  • Don't move comments along with delimiters, which could cause crashes (#4248)
  • Strengthen AST safety check to catch more unsafe changes to strings. Previous versions of Black would incorrectly format the contents of certain unusual f-strings containing nested strings with the same quote type. feat(webapp): Add browser-based UI with Pyodide

This commit introduces a web-based user interface for translating
presentations, making the tool accessible without requiring a local
Python environment.

The UI is a single HTML file that uses Pyodide to run the `pptrans`
package entirely in the browser. Users can upload a `.pptx` file, and
the translation is performed client-side.

Key changes include:
- A new `webapp/` directory containing the `index.html` file.
- JavaScript to load Pyodide, install dependencies, and handle file
  processing.
- A symlink (`webapp/dist`) to serve the Python wheel to the browser.
- A new `.gitignore` file to exclude common artifacts.
- A test script (`tests/create_sample_pptx.py`) and a sample
  presentation (`tests/sample.en.pptx`) for development and testing.

refactor(webapp): Move Python logic to a separate file and add JS type stubs

This commit refactors the web application by moving the Python logic from an inline script in `webapp/index.html` to a dedicated `webapp/index.py` file. This improves code organization and separation of concerns.

To enhance static analysis and code quality, type stubs for the Pyodide `js` module have been added under `src/js/`. This allows `pyright` to type-check the browser-side Python code that interacts with JavaScript APIs.

The project configuration in `pyproject.toml` has been updated to:
- Add `marimo` and `pyodide-py` as development dependencies.
- Adjust `ruff` and `pyright` settings to accommodate the new files and type stubs.
- Change the default branch from `master` to `main` for linting revisions.

Finally, tests for the main application were updated to correctly pass the `from_language` and `to_language` arguments, ensuring the test suite remains consistent with recent feature additions.

ci(github): Add workflows for testing, building, and deployment

This commit introduces three GitHub Actions workflows to automate the
project's CI/CD pipeline.

- `test.yml`: Runs pytest on pushes and pull requests to ensure code
  integrity.
- `build_wheel.yml`: Builds the Python wheel from the source.
- `deploy_pages.yml`: Deploys the `webapp/` directory and the built
  wheel to GitHub Pages, triggered by a successful build.

pull_request.title: Fix test status logic in test_issue_761_fix.py by tracking individual results
pull_request.body:
The test status logic in `test_issue_761_fix.py` was incorrectly tracking test results. The original implementation only counted passed tests without storing individual test results, making it impossible to display which specific tests passed or failed in the summary.

## Problem

The flawed logic assumed tests are processed in order and all passing tests come first:

```python
# Original problematic code
passed_tests = 0
for test_name, test_func in tests:
    if test_func():
        passed_tests += 1

# Only showed total count, no individual status
print(f"Tests passed: {passed_tests}/{total_tests}")
```

This meant the summary could only show the total count but couldn't indicate which individual tests passed or failed.

## Solution

Changed to track individual test results in a list and display individual status using the suggested pattern:

```python
# Fixed implementation
test_results = []
for test_name, test_func in tests:
    try:
        result = test_func()
        test_results.append(result)
    except Exception as e:
        print(f"❌ {test_name}: Exception occurred: {e}")
        test_results.append(False)

# Now shows individual test status
for (test_name, _), result in zip(tests, test_results):
    status = "✅ PASS" if result else "❌ FAIL"
    print(f"{status} {test_name}")
```

## Testing

The fix now correctly displays individual test status like other test files in the repository:

```
✅ PASS Enhanced Workflow Error Handling
✅ PASS Comprehensive Dependency Validation
✅ PASS LaTeX Package Dependency Robustness
✅ PASS Workflow YAML Syntax Robustness
✅ PASS Build System Error Recovery
```

All existing tests continue to pass, and the pattern now matches `test_issue_735_fix.py` and `test_issue_739_fix.py`.

Fixes #815.

issue.title: Add Legrand devices: Connected Outlet, Micromodule Switch, Shutter Switch, Remote Shutter Switch, Switch and Dimmer
issue.body:
## Proposed change

Add some custom Legrand clusters:
* `LegrandIdentify` which extends the `Identify` cluster to support the custom `identify` command needed for Legrand devices, which requires sending a `trigger_effect` command before.
* `LegrandShutterCluster` which extends the `Shutter` cluster adding a `calibration_mode` enum attribute

Support the new following Legrand devices:
* Connected Outlet (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/BTI-N4531C-IT) equivalent by BTicino)
* Micromodule Switch (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/BTI-3584C-IT) equivalent by BTicino)
* Shutter Switches (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/BTI-N4027C-IT) equivalent by BTicino)
* Remote Shutter Switches (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/comandi-wireless-per-gestione-luci-e-tapparelle/BTI-LN4027CWI-IT) equivalent by BTicino)

Convert to quirk V2 the following Legrand devices:
* Switch (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/BTI-N4003C-IT) equivalent by BTcino)
* Dimmer with Neutral (I own [this](https://catalogo.bticino.it/prodotto/soluzioni-per-edifici-residenziali-e-nel-terziario/livinglight/livinglight-smart/BTI-N4411C-IT) equivalent by BTcino)

## Additional information

* The `LegrandCluster` manufacturer specific cluster has been slightly refactored renaming the `dimmer` attribute to `device_mode` and adding some values to be consistent with the Z2M implementation (see [here](https://github.com/Koenkk/zigbee-herdsman-converters/blob/8e9404b28c6b4ee032bb29d6528695e3d260d38f/src/lib/legrand.ts#L205)) 
* I removed from all devices I implemented, the binary input entity (which is non functional)
* I removed from all devices the "opening" entity associated with the OnOff cluster (which is also non functional)
* I added toggle entities to control the LED behavior (led_on_when_on and led_on_when_off, which turn on the integrated LED respectively when the device is in the on or off state)

Information has been derived from the [Legrand developer portal](https://developer.legrand.com/local-interoperability/#Products%20cluster%20list) and the Z2M implementation.

Commits have been separated by domain for easier review, but only tested as a whole (single commits might not be functional)

issue.title: Tracking Open Messages
issue.body:
<!-- Describe the proposal, including how it would help you or your organization. -->

In asynchronous communication, a request message can easily fall through the cracks. But Zulip is perfectly equipped to point out and handle such open ends.

When I ping somebody else in a message, it would be great for me and them to not just find that message by searching for specific pings, but to be able to see if that message was received and addressed. For that one of two options is ideal: a reaction or a reply.

What I propose is (an) extra view(s) under "Views" to track "Loose Ends" / "Unaddressed Messages" or however you want to call it. The idea is that a message shows up there if (1) it contains a mention of a person or group (2) nobody from that person or group has responded or reacted so far. There may be two views, one for messages I sent and one for messages mentioning me, but merging them might be more practical. If multiple people are mentioned separately, their response state should be tracked separately - this also gives distinct practical meaning to mentioning a group vs mentioning the members of a group: do I just want a response or do I want every single person in that group to see it? In the latter case I need to mention them individually instead.

This allows people to rely less on having messages unread through letting Zulip intelligently keep track what is actually still open.

pull_request.title: Refactor: Simplify profile feature navigation
pull_request.body:
This commit refactors the navigation within the profile feature by:

- Removing the dedicated `ProfileNavGraph` and its associated navigator classes (`ProfileNavigator`, `ProfileNavigatorImpl`, `ProfileNavigationEvent`, etc.).
- Introducing a `ProfileDestinationActivity` to handle navigation to `WatchHistoryScreen` and `MyRatingScreen`.
- Navigation to these screens is now done by launching `ProfileDestinationActivity` with the target `Destination` serialized as a JSON string in the Intent extras.
- The `ProfileScreen` is now the direct entry point for the profile feature.
- `BaseViewModel` no longer holds a reference to `ProfileNavigator`.
- Updated `WatchHistoryScreen` and `MyRatingScreen` to use `LocalActivity.current.finish()` for back navigation instead of the ViewModel.
- Added serialization dependency for Kotlinx Serialization.
- Updated `ProfileViewModel` and `ProfileScreen` to use the new navigation mechanism.
- Removed `onBackClick` from `MyRatingViewModel`, `WatchHistoryViewModel`, and their respective interaction listeners.
- Moved `InstallSavedAppLanguage.kt` and `MainViewModel.kt` to a more general `main` package.
- Removed unused `BaseViewModel.kt` from `utils` package and `ObserveAsEvents.kt`.

Add error handling for `Element` lifecycle user callbacks (#173148)

This is for #172289, but since this fix is speculative so I'll wait for
the confirmation from the original reporters before closing the issue.

As a bonus this fixes #65655

The framework Element rebuild logic relies heavily on
`Element._lifecycleState` being correct. When a user-supplied lifecycle
callback (e.g., `State.deactivate`) fails the framework currently only
ensures that every `Element` in the tree has the right lifecycle state,
so an out-of-tree `Element` that is supposed to be disposed may still
have an `active` state and continue being rebuilt by the BuildScope
(because it's in the dirty list). See the comments in #172289

Also related:
#100777
Internal:
b/425298525 b/431537277
b/300829376 b/415724119 b/283614822

# TODO (in a different PR)
The original issue could also be caused by incorrect
`Element.updateChild` calls. If an `Element` subclass calls
`Element.updateChild` to add child but forgets to update its child list
accordingly (such that `visitChildren` misses that child), you'll get a
child Element that thinks it's a child of the parent but the parent
doesn't recognize the child so won't take that child into account during
reparenting or unmounting. This is a programmer error that we should try
to catch in the framework.

feat: add onLongPressUp callback to InkWell widget (#173221)

This PR introduces a new optional callback, onLongPressUp, to the
InkWell widget.
It allows developers to respond specifically to the moment when a long
press gesture is released, which previously was not directly exposed.

**Before**
There was no way to distinguish between the long press being held and
the moment it ended.

**After**
InkWell now accepts an onLongPressUp callback, which fires when the user
lifts their finger after a long press gesture.
This change enhances gesture handling granularity for widgets that
require different behaviors for long press hold and release.


**Related Issue**
#173390

**Tests**
- Added a new test to ink_well_test.dart verifying that onLongPressUp is
correctly triggered after a long press is released.

Predictive back route transitions by default (#165832)

This PR turns on predictive back route transitions by default on
supported Android devices.

With https://github.com/flutter/flutter/pull/154718, the default
(PredictiveBackPageTransitionsBuilder) is the [shared element
transition](https://developer.android.com/design/ui/mobile/guides/patterns/predictive-back#shared-element-transition).
The [full screen
transition](https://developer.android.com/design/ui/mobile/guides/patterns/predictive-back#full-screen-surfaces)
is also available by using
PredictiveBackFullScreenPageTransitionsBuilder.
